{"id":8395,"date":"2017-03-03T23:48:41","date_gmt":"2017-03-04T06:48:41","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/?p=8395"},"modified":"2019-02-15T15:33:19","modified_gmt":"2019-02-15T22:33:19","slug":"aerial-roots-succulents-normal","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/aerial-roots-succulents-normal\/","title":{"rendered":"Are aerial roots on succulents normal?"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><div class=\"fusion-fullwidth fullwidth-box fusion-builder-row-1 nonhundred-percent-fullwidth non-hundred-percent-height-scrolling\" style=\"background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0);background-position: center center;background-repeat: no-repeat;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;margin-bottom: 0px;margin-top: 0px;border-width: 0px 0px 0px 0px;border-color:#eae9e9;border-style:solid;\" ><div class=\"fusion-builder-row fusion-row\"><div class=\"fusion-layout-column fusion_builder_column fusion-builder-column-0 fusion_builder_column_1_1 1_1 fusion-one-full fusion-column-first fusion-column-last\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-column-wrapper fusion-flex-column-wrapper-legacy\" style=\"background-position:left top;background-repeat:no-repeat;-webkit-background-size:cover;-moz-background-size:cover;-o-background-size:cover;background-size:cover;padding: 0px 0px 0px 0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-text fusion-text-1\"><p>If you've had your succulent a while, you may eventually notice some aerial roots or air roots forming along the stem. While this isn't a major problem, it is a sign your succulent needs attention. Find out how to help it below.<\/p>\n<p>I'm guessing you're here because you've found some roots growing from the stem of your succulent, right?<\/p>\n<p>The good news is your succulent is going to be ok. It just needs some extra attention.<\/p>\n<p>Before I get too far in, people frequently ask if aerial roots are a sign their succulent needs water. It can be, and I'll get to that in the post.<\/p>\n<p>But to\u00a0help you even further, start by downloading my <strong>free cheat sheet<\/strong> to see what it looks like when your succulents need more or less water. <span style=\"color: #7e913b;\"><span class=\"tve-leads-two-step-trigger tl-2step-trigger-24596\">Click here to grab that that, it'll be super helpful.<\/span><\/span><\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-8404 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/I-wondered-what-these-were-This-post-explains-everything-you-need-to-know-about-aerial-roots-on-succulents.jpg\" alt=\"I wondered what these were! This post explains everything you need to know about aerial roots on succulents\" width=\"735\" height=\"1102\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/I-wondered-what-these-were-This-post-explains-everything-you-need-to-know-about-aerial-roots-on-succulents-250x375.jpg 250w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/I-wondered-what-these-were-This-post-explains-everything-you-need-to-know-about-aerial-roots-on-succulents-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/I-wondered-what-these-were-This-post-explains-everything-you-need-to-know-about-aerial-roots-on-succulents-585x877.jpg 585w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/I-wondered-what-these-were-This-post-explains-everything-you-need-to-know-about-aerial-roots-on-succulents-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/I-wondered-what-these-were-This-post-explains-everything-you-need-to-know-about-aerial-roots-on-succulents.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>First off, it's probably helpful to know what aerial roots are. Basically, they are just roots that grow on the stem of your succulent rather than in the soil.\u00a0They are usually pink or white.<\/p>\n<h3>What causes aerial roots to grow?<\/h3>\n<p>Generally aerial roots will form on a succulent that isn't getting enough water and often when it's in a humid environment. Succulents absorb water through their roots from the surrounding air.<\/p>\n<p>That is why having a <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/well-draining-soil-for-succulent-container-gardens\/\">soil with large particles<\/a> is really important for the health of your succulent.<\/p>\n<p>If you aren't using the <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/how-to-water-succulent-plants\/\">proper watering technique<\/a> for your succulent, it may not be getting enough water and will start to &#8220;search&#8221; for more. This is when aerial roots start to form.<\/p>\n<p>Your succulent is simply telling you it is thirsty and needs a deeper watering.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-8400 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/A-Graptoveria-Debbie-succulent-with-pink-aerial-roots.jpg\" alt=\"A Graptoveria 'Debbie' succulent with pink aerial roots\" width=\"735\" height=\"1102\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/A-Graptoveria-Debbie-succulent-with-pink-aerial-roots-250x375.jpg 250w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/A-Graptoveria-Debbie-succulent-with-pink-aerial-roots-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/A-Graptoveria-Debbie-succulent-with-pink-aerial-roots-585x877.jpg 585w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/A-Graptoveria-Debbie-succulent-with-pink-aerial-roots-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/A-Graptoveria-Debbie-succulent-with-pink-aerial-roots.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<\/div><div class=\"fusion-text fusion-text-2\"><p>Notice how these <a href=\"http:\/\/www.awin1.com\/cread.php?awinaffid=233213&awinmid=6220&clickref=blog&p=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.etsy.com%2Fsearch%3Fq%3DCrassula%2520rupestris\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow sponsored\">Crassula rupestris<\/a> are extremely dried up at the bottom and have put out a lot of new air roots.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-8399 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/You-may-need-to-water-your-succulents-more-if-you-notice-aerial-roots.jpg\" alt=\"You may need to water your succulents more if you notice aerial roots\" width=\"735\" height=\"1103\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/You-may-need-to-water-your-succulents-more-if-you-notice-aerial-roots-250x375.jpg 250w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/You-may-need-to-water-your-succulents-more-if-you-notice-aerial-roots-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/You-may-need-to-water-your-succulents-more-if-you-notice-aerial-roots-585x878.jpg 585w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/You-may-need-to-water-your-succulents-more-if-you-notice-aerial-roots-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/You-may-need-to-water-your-succulents-more-if-you-notice-aerial-roots.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>This plant is also very <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/stretched-out-succulents\/\">stretched out<\/a> due to lack of sunlight. Lack of sunlight can sometimes cause a succulent to put out air roots.<\/p>\n<p>While this isn't always the case, it is more likely for a succulent to send off aerial roots when it is starting to stretch out.<\/p>\n<h3>Do all succulents grow aerial roots?<\/h3>\n<p>Nope. It tends to be the succulents with a stem, such as <a href=\"https:\/\/leafandclay.co\/products\/awesome-echeveria-pack?variant=31641107406&rfsn=376597.71f09?subid=aerialroots\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow sponsored\">Echeverias<\/a> or tender <a href=\"https:\/\/leafandclay.co\/products\/sedum-rubrotinctum-aurora?variant=28824846723&rfsn=376597.71f09?subid=aerialroots\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow sponsored\">Sedums<\/a>. Generally you won't see aerial roots on <a href=\"https:\/\/leafandclay.co\/products\/haworthia-fasciata?variant=29929903171&rfsn=376597.71f09?subid=aerialroots\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow sponsored\">Haworthias<\/a> or <a href=\"http:\/\/www.awin1.com\/cread.php?awinaffid=233213&awinmid=6220&clickref=blog&p=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.etsy.com%2Fsearch%2Fhandmade%2Fcraft-supplies-and-tools%2Fhome-and-hobby%2Ffloral-and-garden-crafts%2Fgardening-and-plants%3Fq%3Daloe%2520plant%26order%3Dmost_relevant%26ref%3Dauto2%26explicit_scope%3D1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow sponsored\">Aloes<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-8397 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/The-little-white-strands-are-roots-Now-I-know-why-my-succulent-has-them.jpg\" alt=\"The little white strands are roots! Now I know why my succulent has them\" width=\"735\" height=\"1102\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/The-little-white-strands-are-roots-Now-I-know-why-my-succulent-has-them-250x375.jpg 250w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/The-little-white-strands-are-roots-Now-I-know-why-my-succulent-has-them-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/The-little-white-strands-are-roots-Now-I-know-why-my-succulent-has-them-585x877.jpg 585w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/The-little-white-strands-are-roots-Now-I-know-why-my-succulent-has-them-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/The-little-white-strands-are-roots-Now-I-know-why-my-succulent-has-them.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Also, if you are watering correctly, you likely won't see aerial roots at all.<\/p>\n<p>You are more likely to encounter air roots with succulents that grow quickly and are in their active growing season. For example, these <a href=\"https:\/\/mountaincrestgardens.com\/graptoveria-fred-ives\/?afmc=2c\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow sponsored\">Graptoveria &#8216;Fred Ives'<\/a> and <a href=\"https:\/\/mountaincrestgardens.com\/graptopetalum-paraguayense-ghost-plant-mother-of-pearl-plant\/?afmc=2c\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow sponsored\">Graptopetalum paraguayense<\/a> grow quite quickly and tend to stretch out easily if they don't get enough light.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-8403 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Graptoveria-Fred-Ives-with-air-roots.jpg\" alt=\"Graptoveria 'Fred Ives' with air roots\" width=\"735\" height=\"1103\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Graptoveria-Fred-Ives-with-air-roots-250x375.jpg 250w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Graptoveria-Fred-Ives-with-air-roots-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Graptoveria-Fred-Ives-with-air-roots-585x878.jpg 585w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Graptoveria-Fred-Ives-with-air-roots-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Graptoveria-Fred-Ives-with-air-roots.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-8402 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Graptopetalum-paraguayense-with-aerial-roots.jpg\" alt=\"Graptopetalum paraguayense with aerial roots\" width=\"735\" height=\"1102\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Graptopetalum-paraguayense-with-aerial-roots-250x375.jpg 250w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Graptopetalum-paraguayense-with-aerial-roots-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Graptopetalum-paraguayense-with-aerial-roots-585x877.jpg 585w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Graptopetalum-paraguayense-with-aerial-roots-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Graptopetalum-paraguayense-with-aerial-roots.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-8401 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/A-succulent-stem-with-lots-of-aerial-roots.jpg\" alt=\"A succulent stem with lots of aerial roots\" width=\"735\" height=\"1103\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/A-succulent-stem-with-lots-of-aerial-roots-250x375.jpg 250w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/A-succulent-stem-with-lots-of-aerial-roots-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/A-succulent-stem-with-lots-of-aerial-roots-585x878.jpg 585w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/A-succulent-stem-with-lots-of-aerial-roots-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/A-succulent-stem-with-lots-of-aerial-roots.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Again, you'll notice that these plants are all very stretched out. The Graptopetalum paraguayense also has limp wrinkled leaves indicating that it needs more water.<\/p>\n<h3>What should I do about the air roots?<\/h3>\n<p>You don't need to remove the roots, although you can if they are getting too unsightly. However, be sure to <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/how-to-water-succulent-plants\/\">water your succulent more deeply<\/a>\u00a0(not necessarily more often) and make sure it is getting plenty of light.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-8396 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Sedum-rubrotinctum-frequently-grows-air-roots-when-it-isnt-getting-enough-water.jpg\" alt=\"Sedum rubrotinctum frequently grows air roots when it isn't getting enough water\" width=\"735\" height=\"1103\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Sedum-rubrotinctum-frequently-grows-air-roots-when-it-isnt-getting-enough-water-250x375.jpg 250w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Sedum-rubrotinctum-frequently-grows-air-roots-when-it-isnt-getting-enough-water-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Sedum-rubrotinctum-frequently-grows-air-roots-when-it-isnt-getting-enough-water-585x878.jpg 585w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Sedum-rubrotinctum-frequently-grows-air-roots-when-it-isnt-getting-enough-water-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/03\/Sedum-rubrotinctum-frequently-grows-air-roots-when-it-isnt-getting-enough-water.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>If you leave the roots attached, they may eventually harden or thicken and look like a small branch. This is normal.<\/p>\n<p>While aerial roots aren't a huge problem, they are something you should be aware of so you know how to adjust the care of your succulent. This is an early warning sign that your succulent isn't as healthy as it could be.<\/p>\n<p>And remember, if you haven't already, be sure to download my <strong>free cheat sheet<\/strong> to see what it looks like when your succulents need more or less water. <span style=\"color: #7e913b;\"><span class=\"tve-leads-two-step-trigger tl-2step-trigger-24596\">Click here to get the cheatsheet.<\/span><\/span><\/p>\n<\/div><div class=\"fusion-text fusion-text-3\"><p><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">.<\/span><\/p>\n<\/div><div class=\"fusion-clearfix\"><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><div class=\"fusion-fullwidth fullwidth-box fusion-builder-row-2 nonhundred-percent-fullwidth non-hundred-percent-height-scrolling\" style=\"background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0);background-position: center center;background-repeat: no-repeat;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;margin-bottom: 0px;margin-top: 0px;border-width: 0px 0px 0px 0px;border-color:#eae9e9;border-style:solid;\" ><div class=\"fusion-builder-row fusion-row\"><div class=\"fusion-layout-column fusion_builder_column fusion-builder-column-1 fusion_builder_column_1_1 1_1 fusion-one-full fusion-column-first fusion-column-last\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-column-wrapper fusion-flex-column-wrapper-legacy\" style=\"background-position:left top;background-repeat:no-repeat;-webkit-background-size:cover;-moz-background-size:cover;-o-background-size:cover;background-size:cover;padding: 0px 0px 0px 0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-text fusion-text-4\"><p><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">.<\/span><\/p>\n<\/div><div class=\"fusion-clearfix\"><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"","protected":false},"author":7,"featured_media":15930,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":[],"categories":[1,68,45,127],"tags":[209,81],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/8395"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"